efield, to political detainees, to those suffering the effects of natural disasters. The world’s oldest and most preeminent humanitarian movement, the relevance and status of the Red Cross Movement today is as high as it has ever been.Reimagining and re-evaluating the Red Cross as a global institutional network, this volume charts the rise of the Red Cross and analyses the emergence of humanitarianism through a series of turning points, practices and myths. The contributors explore the three unique elements that make up the Red Cross Movement: the International Committee of the Red Cross, the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent formerly known as the League of Red Cross Societies (both based in Geneva) and the 192 national societies. With chapters by leading scholars and researchers from Europe, the United Kingdom, Australia, New Zealand and America, the book offers a timely account of this unique, complex and contested organisation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aInternational Relations 2020. 4aPolitical Studies 2021. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aHealth service.  aHumanitarianism.  aInternational Committee of the Red Cross.  aInternational Federation of Red Cross Red Crescent.  aInternational organisations.  aLeague of Red Cross Societies.  aMedicine.  aRed Cross.  aRelief.  aWar.1 aArrizabalaga, Jon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCresswell, Rosemary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrossland, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrossland, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aF. S. Lopes, Helena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcía-Reyes, J. Carlos, econt